  "prompt": "Is it not true that Kejriwal too started to play dirty politics?",
  "response": "Arvind Kejriwal, the Chief Minister of Delhi and leader of the Aam Aadmi Party (AAP), has faced various criticisms and allegations from political opponents and critics that accuse him of engaging in \"dirty politics.\" These claims often pertain to accusations of populism, alleged manipulation of public sentiment, tactical political moves, and confrontational approaches against opponents. However, such critiques are a common occurrence in politics and often depend on one's perspective and political inclinations.\n\nSupporters of Kejriwal argue that his actions stem from a genuine commitment to addressing corruption and promoting transparency, which were key tenets of his political platform when he first entered politics. They tend to view his strategies as necessary to combat established political structures and to advocate for issues that they believe are neglected by other politicians.\n\nIt's important to note that in politics, the definition of \"dirty\" can vary significantly based on one's viewpoint. What some may see as strategic maneuvering, others may interpret as unethical behavior. \n\nUltimately, whether Kejriwal is playing \"dirty politics\" is a matter of perspective and is influenced heavily by the political and social lenses through which individuals view his actions.",
